The data set contains 124372 observations and 16 columns. These inspections are taken by the Chicago Department of Public Healths Food Protection for businesses that sell food within the city limits of Chicago, including grocery stores, restaurants, and bakeries. The original data source can be found here : https://data.cityofchicago.org/Health-Human-Services/Food-Inspections/4ijn-s7e5.

Motivation

We can use this data set to answer a variety of questions regarding food inspections in Chicago. With over 124,000 businesses or establishments and 2.5 million Chicagoans using their services in their day to day life, it is important to gauge an idea of the overall safety and health conditions of these places. This data analysis website will provide valuable insights and information on inspection data all over Chicago and help residents and visitors make informed decisions on where they want to go.

Problem [1]

We want to look at the severity of violations in different regions of Chicago. Are severe violations (critical or serious violation) more common in the northern part of Chicago or the southern part of Chicago?

Plan

First, dictate the difference between northern and southern Chicago by taking the range of the latitude (max and min) and finding its average. If the latitude is higher than the average, we characterize it as northern Chicago. Otherwise, it is characterized as southern Chicago. Next, create two new data frames for each portion of the city and plot businesses that had a severe violation and those that did not for each portion. Finally, numerically view these results in a table and calculate the proportion of severe violations for each data frame.

Data

Find the average latitude by taking the average of the min and max latitude.

Latitude_Min <- min(FoodData$Latitude)
Latitude_Max <- max(FoodData$Latitude)

Center_Latitude <- (Latitude_Min + Latitude_Max)/2

Center_Latitude
## [1] 41.83287

Ceate two new data frames, one for southern Chicago and one for northern Chicago.

NorthChicago <- filter(FoodData, Latitude > Center_Latitude)
SouthChicago <- filter(FoodData, Latitude < Center_Latitude)

Plot the violation severity for businesses in northern Chicago. The blue + indicates a violation severity of 1 while the red x indicates a violation severity of 0.

ggplot(data = NorthChicago, mapping = aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude)) +
  geom_point(data = filter(NorthChicago, violation_severity == 1), color = "blue", pch = 3) +
  geom_point(data = filter(NorthChicago, violation_severity == 0), color = "red", pch = 4)

Plot the violation severity for businesses in southern Chicago. The blue + indicates a violation severity of 1 while the red x indicates a violation severity of 0.

ggplot(data = SouthChicago, mapping = aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude)) +
  geom_point(data = filter(SouthChicago, violation_severity == 1), color = "blue", pch = 3) +
  geom_point(data = filter(SouthChicago, violation_severity == 0), color = "red", pch = 4)

Values for each violation severity type in northern Chicago.

table(NorthChicago$violation_severity)
## 
##     0     1 
## 58710 33812

Values for each violation severity type in southern Chicago.

table(SouthChicago$violation_severity)
## 
##     0     1 
## 20505 11345

Finding the proportion of businesses with a violation severity of 1 in northern Chicago and southern Chicago.

NorthChicagoProportion <- ((sum(NorthChicago$violation_severity == 1))/nrow(NorthChicago))*100
NorthChicagoProportion
## [1] 36.54482
SouthChicagoProportion <- ((sum(SouthChicago$violation_severity == 1))/nrow(SouthChicago))*100
SouthChicagoProportion
## [1] 35.62009

Analysis

From the plots, we can see that there appears to be more red points than blue points in both northern and southern Chicago, indicating that businesses are more likely to have no severe violations. This is confirmed in the table where we see that northern Chicago has 58,710 businesses with no severe violations and 33,812 with serious violations. Likewise, southern Chicago has 20,505 businesses with no severe violations and 11,345 with serious violations. In northern Chicago, 36.54% of businesses have severe violations while in southern Chicago, this figure is slightly lower, at 35.62%.

Conclusion

While the proportions are extremely close and separated by less than a percent, we can conclude that severe violations are more common in Northern Chicago.

Problem [2]

Building off the previous question, I thought it would be interesting to see how the western and eastern halves compare. This time, instead of filtering by violation severity, we can filter by the result of the inspection and see if failure rates are higher in the western part of Chicago or in the eastern part of Chicago?

Plan

First, dictate the difference between eastern and western Chicago by taking the range of the longitude (max and min) and finding its average. Since the longitude of Chicago is negative, if the longitude is higher than the average, we characterize it as eastern Chicago. Otherwise, it is characterized as western Chicago. Next, create two new data frames for each portion of the city and plot businesses by their pass rate and fail rate. We can combine pass rate and pass with conditions rate in this case since we only want to compare the total pass rate versus the fail rate. Finally, numerically view these results in a table and calculate the proportion of failing inspections for each data frame.

Find the average longitude by taking the average of the min and max longitude.

Longtitude_Min <- min(FoodData$Longitude)
Longtitude_Max <-max(FoodData$Longitude)

Center_Longitude <- (Longtitude_Min + Longtitude_Max)/2

Center_Longitude
## [1] -87.71976

Create two new data frames, one for eastern Chicago and one for western Chicago.

EastChicago <- filter(FoodData, Longitude > Center_Longitude)
WestChicago <- filter(FoodData, Longitude < Center_Longitude)

Plot the businesses that passed and failed in eastern Chicago. The orange + indicates that the business passed while the purple x indicates that the business failed.

ggplot(data = EastChicago, mapping = aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude)) +
  geom_point(data = filter(EastChicago, Results == "Pass"), color = "orange", pch = 3) +
  geom_point(data = filter(EastChicago, Results == "Pass w/ conditions"), color = "orange", pch = 3) +
  geom_point(data = filter(EastChicago, Results == "Fail"), color = "purple", pch = 4)

Plot the businesses that passed and failed in western Chicago. The blue + indicates that the business passed while the red x indicates that the business failed.

ggplot(data = WestChicago, mapping = aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude)) +
  geom_point(data = filter(WestChicago, Results == "Pass"), color = "orange", pch = 3) +
  geom_point(data = filter(WestChicago, Results == "Pass w/ conditions"), color = "orange", pch = 3) +
  geom_point(data = filter(WestChicago, Results == "Fail"), color = "purple", pch = 4)

Proportions for failing businesses in eastern Chicago.

EastChicagoProportion <- ((sum(EastChicago$Results == "Fail"))/nrow(EastChicago))*100
EastChicagoProportion
## [1] 24.54595

Proportions for failing businesses in western Chicago.

WestChicagoProportion <- ((sum(WestChicago$Results == "Fail"))/nrow(WestChicago))*100
WestChicagoProportion
## [1] 22.48151

Analysis

From the plots, we can see that there appears to be about an even number of orange and purple points in both eastern and western Chicago, indicating that the pass and fail rate is similar. This is opposed by table of proportions, where 24.55% of businesses in eastern Chicago get a failing result while 22.48% of businesses in western Chicago get a failing result.

Conclusion

Once again, although these numbers are not far off, eastern Chicago has higher fail rates. We can conclude that failure rates are common in the eastern part of Chicago than in the western part of Chicago.

Problem [3]

After factoring in regional effects, we can broaden our scope to the entire city and we can see how does the level of risk affect if an establishment passed or failed inspection?

Plan

Plot each risk level (Risk 1, Risk 2, Risk 3) in a histogram, filtering individual bars into 3 sections for each of the 3 results (Pass, Fail, Pass with conditions). Afterwards, put this information into a table and find the total proportion of pass, pass with conditions, and fail rates for each of the 3 risk levels.

Data

Plotting the count of the result type for each risk level.

ggplot(data = FoodData ) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = factor(Risk), fill = factor(Results)) , position = "stack") +
  labs(x= "Risk Level", title = "Failure and passing rate for each risk level") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Type of result"))

Values for each combination of risk level and result type.

table(FoodData$Risk, FoodData$Results)
##                  
##                    Fail  Pass Pass w/ Conditions
##   Risk 1 (High)   21429 59797              12427
##   Risk 2 (Medium)  5938 14543               3395
##   Risk 3 (Low)     2642  3842                359

Calculating the individiual proportions of passing, passing with conditions, and failing for each risk level.

HRPass <- 59797/ (sum(FoodData$Risk == "Risk 1 (High)"))

MRPass <- 14543/ (sum(FoodData$Risk == "Risk 2 (Medium)"))

LRPass <- 3842/ (sum(FoodData$Risk == "Risk 3 (Low)"))

HRPWC <- 12427/ (sum(FoodData$Risk == "Risk 1 (High)"))

MRPWC <- 3395/ (sum(FoodData$Risk == "Risk 2 (Medium)"))

LRPWC <- 395/ (sum(FoodData$Risk == "Risk 3 (Low)"))

HRFail <- 1 - HRPass - HRPWC

MRFail <- 1 - MRPass - MRPWC

LRFail <- 1 - LRPass - LRPWC

Proportions of high risk businesses passing, passing with conditions, and failing.

HRPass
## [1] 0.6384953
HRPWC
## [1] 0.132692
HRFail
## [1] 0.2288127

Proportions of medium risk businesses passing, passing with conditions, and failing.

MRPass
## [1] 0.6091054
MRPWC
## [1] 0.142193
MRFail
## [1] 0.2487016

Proportions of low risk businesses passing, passing with conditions, and failing.

LRPass
## [1] 0.5614497
LRPWC
## [1] 0.05772322
LRFail
## [1] 0.3808271

Analysis

From the proportion tables, we can see the percentage of each result at each risk level. For high risk businesses, the proportion of passing rates are 0.6385, passing with conditions is 0.1327, and failing is 0.2288. For medium risk risk businesses, the proportion of passing rates are 0.6091, passing with conditions is 0.1422, and failing is 0.2487. For medium risk businesses, the proportion of passing rates are 0.5614, passing with conditions is 0.0577, and failing is 0.3809. Finally, for low risk businesses, the proportion of passing rates are 0.5614, passing with conditions is 0.0577, and failing is 0.3809. We can see that high risk businesses actually have higher passing rates than medium risk and low risk businesses. High risk businesses also have higher passing with conditions rates and therefore have lower failure rates than medium and low risk businesses.

Conclusion

We can see that we got an opposite result than expected, as high risk businesses have a higher passing rate and lower failure rate than low risk businesses. Therefore, we can conclude that the level of risk does not affect or determine if an establishment passed or failed inspection.

Problem [4]

Finally, we want to see how a customer complaint can affect the the inspection outcome of a business. Are busineses that get a complaint more likely to pass inspection or not pass/ fail inspection?

Plan

First, filter the data with only businesses that received a complaint. Next, we can make a bar chart visualizing the number of businesses that passed inspection or did not pass. Finally, numerically visualize these results in a table to see the raw number of values in each instance to determine what is more likely.

Data

Filtering the data set to only include businesses with complaints.

ComplaintData <- filter(FoodData, `Inspection Type` == "Complaint")

Plotting the bar chart for businesses with passing and failing inspections.

ggplot(data = ComplaintData) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = factor(pass_or_not)), fill = "blue") +
  labs(x= "Passing(1) or Not Passing(0)", title = "Number of Businesses With Complaints Passing and Failing Inspection") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Blacks vs All other races"))

Putting the data into a table.

table(ComplaintData$`Inspection Type`, ComplaintData$pass_or_not)
##            
##                0    1
##   Complaint 7720 7121

Analysis

From the bar chart, we can see that there are more 0 values (failing/ not passing) than 1 values (passing). This is confirmed in the table since there 7720 businesses with a complaint that fail inspection compared to 7121 businesses with a complaint that pass.

Conclusion

We see that this is a significant difference of 599, or an 8.07% difference. We can conclude that businesses that get a complaint are more likely to not pass or fail their inspection.

Final Takeaway

After running all four problems in our investigative cycle, we get a good idea of food inspection data in Chicago. Residents and tourists can have a good sense of where and where not to go within Chicago the next time they decide to go to a food establishment. This website can help millions of people make informed decisions and maintain their safety and well being when eating within Chicago.
